  "text": "Mattei et al. [CITATION_1] Theorem 6] showed that WEIGHTED-(SM, A, C)-BRIBERY is N Pcomplete for all bribery actions and for all cost schemes they considered. However, for the cost schemes C ∈ {C LEVEL , C DIST , C FLIP , C ANY }, their reduction implicitly makes use of the cost vector Q. Hence, the computational hardness originates from the individual costs for each voter. This is not the case for C EQUAL , where N P-completeness already follows from the result in the unweighted case, without any requirement on individual costs.",
